    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-2428907">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-2428907">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2428907)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2428907">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/eta-carinae" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2110706); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2110706&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610225812" alt="Eta Carinae" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2110706)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/eta-carinae" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2110706); return false;" >Eta Carinae</a></span> <span class="odate time_1450949368 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">24 Dec 2015 09:29</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2428907">
									

<p>No, no, MrWrong, you've got it wrong.<br />
055 is <span style="text-decoration: underline;">not a sphere</span>.<br />
And Santa is not a sphere either.<br />
Ergo, Santa <em>is</em> 055.</p>
<p>We could use some cold here too. Some plants in the garden are <em>blooming</em>. And if it goes on like this, we shall be completely invaded by instances of SCP-006-J (especially SCP-006-J-1, the stupid little fuckers) by March.</p>
<p>Now. May I nitpick about a few things, my tropical friend? ;&gt;</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>I've noticed recently a few tales that mix up sentences in present tense and in past tense. It never fails to disturb me. IMO, you can do this, but it has to be deliberate and meaningful, for effect: for instance, to suddenly speed up a scene when some action takes place.<br />
So, I would put all these sentences in past tense:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>He was a fairly obese man of pale complexion, with round chest and belly. Donned in red and white, he was silent and stealthy. In his hands, he carried an equally round red sack that rattled and jingled every step the man took. This man was Santa, obviously.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>OTOH, I wouldn't object to this being in present tense:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>But suddenly…<br />
&quot;Hey there!&quot; a voice cries.<br />
Santa turns around calmly and he sees a young boy, most likely aged between six to nine. The young boy is holding an action figure of a brass robot, worn with age – the many years it has been in this boy's possession. The young boy stares blankly at this stout stranger in front of him, trying his hardest not to blink.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>then back to past tense&#8230;!</p>
<p>Also, I think sometimes you tend to spell everything out, which weighs down your style and story. For instance:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>But in the end, the temptation to blink was too potent and the boy blinked. Santa was no longer by the Christmas tree; he was right in front of the boy <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">with gift box still in hand</span>. He bent down again and presented the boy with the gift box.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This way, the storytelling is quicker and lighter, with no repetition. What do you think?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;Little Fred, I presume? Take it.&quot;<br />
The boy <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">– named Fred –</span> accepted the gift box, dropping his brass action figure in the process. He shook the box, <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">thinking</span> wondering what it could be. All this time, Santa looked on with a gentle smile on his face.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The mother is going to call him Fred a few lines further down: you could easily do without this &quot;- named Fred&quot;.</p>
<p>You could switch again to present tense for the mother's appearance, for fun effect.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The hallways of Site-19 are long and winding, although Santa knew his way around well enough.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>For some reason, present tense looks right here, even if you switch back to past in the same sentence. Don't ask me why. Please. Just feels right!!!!<br />
Same with this:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The door opened on its own accord, as though it noticed Santa's presence. Inside is an empty room of concrete with a Faraday cage. Santa entered the room</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Yeah. The mysteries of good writing&#8230;!</p>
<blockquote>
<p>He entered the cells of one his assigned SCPs, in a room with a Faraday cage Inside</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Should be:<br />
<em>He entered the <span style="text-decoration: underline;">cell</span> of one <span style="text-decoration: underline;">of</span> his assigned <span style="text-decoration: underline;">SCPs: a</span> room with a Faraday cage inside</em><br />
What do you think?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>a bit of humour and entertainment keep us sane</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Should be 'keep<span style="text-decoration: underline;">s</span> us sane' (subject of the verb is 'bit', = singular)</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Besides, it'll be the Sites for us on the 26th</p>
</blockquote>
<p>What do you mean?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Even father couldn't convince him to</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Should be <span style="text-decoration: underline;">F</span>ather</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The door bell to the Hu residence rang, while An kept on typing.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This (and the rest of the paragraph) could be in present tense again.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>I must say I don't quite understand the link between the two parts of your tale (Santa -&gt; the Hu family), but&#8230; hey, why not?</p>
<p>No vote for now. I do believe your tale needs a wee bit of tightening up!</p>
<p>Oh, BTW: I'm rather surprised that Santa Claus is not already an SCP with its own huge canon hub&#8230; Or have I not searched properly? ;&gt;</p>

							</div>

								
					
